Welcome to Timeseria!¶

Timeseria is about doing time series right. It is build form scratch to do not pretend that time series data is just a single-dimenson data (i.e. x,y values) and to take in account by design both physical time (hours, minutes, seconds) and logical time (days, months, years), so that for example you won't get mad with daylight saving times anymore. It aslo provides a firm disticntion between Points and Slots, where Points are observations (that can be uneven, unequealm etc.) while Slots are a way of discretising the time dimension upscaling or downscaling observational DataPoints tio provide a unifor, continuow, well coveraed, dense (discretized time.dimenstion).

Let's start with a few concepts.

Basic data structures¶

Points are the most basic datastructure. They can be initialized in any n-dimensional space you want. The following example is in a x,y space but it could be also i,j,k.

In [2]:
from timeseria.datastructures import Point
point = Point(x=1,y=2)
print(point)

Point with {'x': 1, 'y': 2}

You can access the coordinates as attributes:

In [3]:
print('Point x coordinate: {}'.format(point.x))

Point x coordinate: 1

TimePoints are Points in the "time" dimesntion. They must be initialised in the "t" coordinate, wich is epoch, or the number of seconds from 1st January 1970 UTC. Milliseconds, microscodns etc. can be expressed using the deciamal palces.

In [4]:
from timeseria.datastructures import TimePoint
timePoint = TimePoint(t=60)
print(timePoint)

TimePoint @ t=60 (1970-01-01 00:01:00+00:00)

TimePoints tiem component can also be accessed (and set) as Python DateTime objects using "dt" instead of "t":

In [5]:
print(timePoint.dt)

1970-01-01 00:01:00+00:00

DataPoints are Points with some data attached. This data can be whatever you want: a string, an image, a single value, a list of values, a dict of values. However, most of the functionalities of Timeseria require it to be in the form of a list of numerical values or a dict of numerical values, which is the format that will be used in the following.

In [6]:
from timeseria.datastructures import DataPoint
dataPoint = DataPoint(x=1, y=2, data='Hello world!')
print(dataPoint)

DataPoint with {'x': 1, 'y': 2} and data "Hello world!"

This concep, of encapsulating data on another level in respect to the coordinates, is one of the main building pillars of timeseria.

We won’t therefore handle matrix of x, y data where x is the time and y is the value, instead will have a key for the time and the data as its value. This makes extremely easier to handle multivariate data and allows, for example, a time series of images to be handled in exact same way as a time series of floating point values (except from the analysis that you will perform on it, of course)

DataTimePoints are TimePoints with some data attached (or, if you prefer, they can also be seen as DataPoints in the time dimension). They are definied by just mergin these two classes. They are the second most important datastructure in Timeseria. The following is an example with data in the form of a list of a single value.

In [7]:
from timeseria.datastructures import DataTimePoint
dataTimepoint = DataTimePoint(t=60, data=[56.8])
print(dataTimepoint)

DataTimePoint @ t=60 (1970-01-01 00:01:00+00:00) with data=[56.8]

A DataTimePointSerie is a series of DataTimePoints. No, the "Serie" withouth the "s" is not a typo, it is intended to mark the difference betwee a single time series and more than one. Also note thata all the other "components", like the Serie, the PointSerie, the TimePointSerie and the DataPointSerie are all defined and useful in other situations.

Creating a DataTimePointSerie it is as simple as creating a classic Python list:

In [8]:
from timeseria.datastructures import DataTimePointSerie

dataTimePointSerie = DataTimePointSerie(DataTimePoint(t=60, data=[5.8]),
                                        DataTimePoint(t=120, data=[6.1]),
                                        DataTimePoint(t=180, data=[5.7]),
                                        DataTimePoint(t=240, data=[4.8]))

As a python list you can also append:

In [9]:
dataTimePointSerie.append(DataTimePoint(t=300, data=[5.1]))

Now, the beauty of Timeseria is that from now on you only neet to care about how to maniplate the DataTimePointSerie object, you don't really care about all the internals. This will be particularly useful when analysign timeseries or creating and evaluating Machine Learning models, as everything will be very intuitive without the typical vector transformations required by a "classic" numpy/pandas approach.

For example, to plot it:

In [10]:
dataTimePointSerie.plot()

This is not the classic Jupyter plot, it is an advanced plot powed by Dygraphs which is designed exclusively for time series data. It smoothly handles thousands of datapoints, and with Timeseria you can even plot millions of them, since it will aggregate them to prevent crashing your browser as we will see in a moment. Try to zoom-in by highlighting a region, move the slider and then double-click to reset the zoom.

However, if you are a Matplot affectionado, you can have that plots too, just by using dataTimePointSerie.plot(engine='mp')

Data Storages¶

To load and store data Timeseria uses the Storage objects. A few example are a CSV file, a SQLite database, a Postgres database, or even a distributed NoSQL system. The idea is that you can wrap whatever put and get logic in a Storage object, thus decaoupling the data storage step from the data processing.

The most simple sotrage is the CSVFileStorage, let's see an example in read mode:

In [11]:
from timeseria import storages
TEST_DATA_PATH = '/'.join(storages.__file__.split('/')[0:-1]) + '/tests/test_data/csv/'

storage = storages.CSVFileStorage(TEST_DATA_PATH+'/temp_long_10m.csv')
dataTimePointSerie = storage.get()

print(dataTimePointSerie)

DataTimePointSerie of #19140 DataTimePoints, from TimePoint @ t=1546477200.0 (2019-01-03 01:00:00+00:00) to TimePoint @ t=1557960600.0 (2019-05-15 22:50:00+00:00)
In [12]:
dataTimePointSerie.plot()

INFO:timeseria.plots:Aggregating by "10" for plotting

Try to zoom in, and you will see that this is nto exactly only a line chart - instead, it is a line chart plus an area chart. This is because Timseria aggrgated the datapoints before plotting them (by a factor of 10 in this case) but it also reported the min and max value for each aggregation interval, rendered via the area chart. This is how Timeseria allows to easily visualize millions of datapoints, yet not removing much of information and most importantly not hiding spikes.

Slots¶

Unitl now we assumed data cleand, evenly samples, qith no gaps. But this is far form reality. In the real world, there will be missing data and physical environments (i.e. sensors) there will also be inconsistent data (different sampling fequency).

Let's have a look at the same time serie that we plotted above but in the real world, and let's plot it without any plot-level aggregation to have get a clear idea about its data points:

In [13]:
storage = storages.CSVFileStorage(TEST_DATA_PATH+'/temperature.csv')
dataTimePointSerie = storage.get()
print(dataTimePointSerie)
dataTimePointSerie.plot(aggregate_by=None)

DataTimePointSerie of #18331 DataTimePoints, from TimePoint @ t=1546477200.0 (2019-01-03 01:00:00+00:00) to TimePoint @ t=1557960000.0 (2019-05-15 22:40:00+00:00)

As you may notice by naked eye there are a few gaps, most notably the one just immediately after the start and the one at around 2/3 of the time series but there are other ones scattered around.

Now, almost everything in time series analysis assumes a discretization of the time in steps of equal length.

What we want is therefore a "dense" discretisation of the time axies, wiht no gaps. To remove gaps, you first have yo know that there is a gap, the the most straightforward way of filling it would be by interpolation or a similar technique.

But then, are you sure that you want to train a model on that interpolated data as whell? Do you want to include in in your stas? If yes, with the some weight? And if not, how do you know how they propagate across aggregated analyses?

Moreover, time steps are quite naturally identified with a specific point in time when the sampling rate is frequent (i.e. a data point every minute), but when it comes hourly of worse daily sampling intervals (or aggregates), the punctual definition of the ti me steps just falls apart: do we identify the hour by the starting point? By the center point of the hour?

The truth is than when we talk about the data acquired at 15:06:00 with 1-minute sampling frequencly, this actually represents data from 15:05:30 to 15:06:30, therefore iw we sample data every hour we should indicate that data acquired at 15:00 is actualy reprentative of what happened between 14:30 to 15:30. if it is not, then the sampling rate is too low, that's math.

Things get ever worse when we tald about days, months and years: while hours and minute intervals have always the same leght in seconds (60 and 3600, respectively), a day can last And the day, do we identify it with midnight? If so when does it ends? not 24 hours later, because this would break over summertime changes.

To properly address all these concepts, Timesera formalises and introduces a completely different concept form the Point: the Slot.

A Slot unlike a Point, it is not identified by a single coordinate, but by a starting point and and ending point. It is defined trought a span, which is basically its duration.

As for the DataTimePoints we have DataTimeSlots, and the DataTimeSLotSeries: the datastructure designed to hold a series of DataTimSlots which requires the slots to cover "densely" the time exis, or in other words that every slot ending point corresponds to the next slot starting point.

DataTimeSlots uses the TimeSpan object as span, which can handle boh "physical" and "human" times, where "physical" times are all the time units not dependent by a calendar like seconds, minutes and hours whil "human" time units that do dependend on a calendar, like days, weeks, months, and years. Slots defined by a "human" timespan, like "1D" for one day and "1M" for one month can have therefore different durations even if they represent the same conceptual duration, and they support time math so that you can sum a month after another or

A slot also has a coverage: this represents how well the slot is "covered" by the underlying datapoints. If you for example have hourly slots and hourly data points, the slot coverage could be either 0 or 1 (assuming data being aligned), but if instead you have hourly slots computed out from 10-minute data points, and you miss two of them for a given slot, this slot will have coverage of (0.66)

The data loss is then just defined as 1-coverage and is quite useful from an intuitive point ov view, i.e. in the graphs.

To compute Slots from Points, Timeseria uses the Slotter operator. Let's see how it works when applied on a time series with gaps:

In [14]:
from timeseria.operators import Slotter
slotter = Slotter('10m')
dataTimeSlotSerie = slotter.process(dataTimePointSerie)
print(dataTimeSlotSerie)

INFO:timeseria.operators:Auto-detected dataTimePoints validity: 600.0 s

DataTimeSlotSerie of #19138 10m DataTimeSlots, from TimePoint @ t=1546477200.0 (2019-01-03 01:00:00+00:00) to TimePoint @ t=1557960000 (2019-05-15 22:40:00+00:00)

As you can see, Timeseria automatically detected the sampling frequency (10 minutes in this case), buy you can alse set it manually, and there is also (limited) support for variable sampling frequencies defined ona per-DataTimePoint basis. Then, it created 10-minite slots as we asked for witht the Slotter object initialised with "10m".

I we now plot this time series, it will appear differently that the ones below. First of all you can see the data loss (renderd as the ligh red red bars), then if you zoom in and mouseover the "points" you will se that this is actually a step plot and that every segment of the plot represents a value for a time span, or our DataTimeSlot.

In [15]:
dataTimeSlotSerie.plot(aggregate_by=None)

We can create slots of watherver time span we want, here is an example with 1 hour and 43 minutes slots (just in case you want things more fun), and below a more realist example of slots of 6 hours.

In [16]:
slotter = Slotter('103m')
dataTimeSlotSerie = slotter.process(dataTimePointSerie)
print(dataTimeSlotSerie)
dataTimeSlotSerie.plot()

INFO:timeseria.operators:Auto-detected dataTimePoints validity: 600.0 s

DataTimeSlotSerie of #1857 103m DataTimeSlots, from TimePoint @ t=1546483200 (2019-01-03 02:40:00+00:00) to TimePoint @ t=1557959460 (2019-05-15 22:31:00+00:00)
In [17]:
slotter = Slotter('6h')
dataTimeSlotSerie = slotter.process(dataTimePointSerie)
print(dataTimeSlotSerie)
dataTimeSlotSerie.plot()

INFO:timeseria.operators:Auto-detected dataTimePoints validity: 600.0 s

DataTimeSlotSerie of #530 6h DataTimeSlots, from TimePoint @ t=1546495200 (2019-01-03 06:00:00+00:00) to TimePoint @ t=1557943200 (2019-05-15 18:00:00+00:00)

Data reconstruction¶

Ok, so now we have a way (the data_loss) to understand how much we can "trust" our data. You can stop here and just use Timeseria as a pre-processing toolkit, or you can read more about the other features that Timeseria has to offer, as the data reconstruction and Machine Learning models.
